@NT = Samay<193>c<193>ra Tantra
The Samay<193>c<193>ra Tantra is considered as an important work ç
among the 64 tantras. Spread over 281 verses in the anu<218><219>ubh ç
metre it deals with all aspects of tantra literature, though briefly.
Practices of v<193>m<193>c<193>ra (See under <MS>TANTRAS<D>.) find ç
a prominent place.
The word `samay<193>c<193>ra' refers to the system of worship and ç
allied details, as applied to a specified deity.
It also means the Dev<200> or the Divine Mother.
Some of the topics dealt with in thiswork may now be described briefly: ç
materials to be used in worship as also those which can be consumed ç
after offering; various times of the day suitable for different rites ç
with specific results like ·<193>ntikarmas (rites for peace) or va·ya-karma ç
(getting others under one's control) and so on; the various <193>sanas ç
or postures to be adopted according to the results desired, like padm<193>sana ç
in peace-rites; certain aspects of the theory involving the books ç
and deities of this school; certain types of m<193>l<193>s (rosaries) ç
and the results of using them; various types of <193>sanas or seats ç
and the results of their use as for instance the tiger-skin being ç
used if one wants mok<218>a (liberation); descriptions of places suitable ç
for the performance of japa (repetition of mantra); classification ç
of mantras as pu<221> (male), str<200> (female) and napu<221>saka ç
(neuter); two types of practices, v<193>m<193>c<193>ra and dak<218>i<207><193>cara ç
(the left-hand  and  the  right-hand  paths); qualities of a guru ç
or teacher and the ·i<218>ya or disciple; various articles needed ç
for p<220>j<193> especially the ones known as pa<210>camak<193>ras ç
(See <MS>TANTRAS<D>.); description of p<200><219>has or seats suitable ç
for the performance of japa, they being the <185>akti-p<200><219>has, ç
places hallowed by the body-parts of Sat<200>†D<193>k<218><193>ya<207><200> ç
(See <MS>TANTRAS<D>); giving of balis (ceremonial offerings) to various ç
deities; certain mantras concerning the various aspects of <185>iva ç
like Aghora; and methods of purifying mantras known as mantrasa<221>sk<193>ra ç
(See <MS>MANTRASA<189>SK°RA<D> for details).
Though a small work, it contains a lot of information about the practical ç
aspects of tantras, more attention being given to the v<193>m<193>c<193>ra ç
practices.
