@SB = Introduction
Sa<221>sk<216>ta or the Sanskrit language has always been held in ç
high veneration by the Hindus, so much so that it has been christened ç
as `Devabh<193><218><193>' (`language of the gods'). The gods in heaven ç
are veryhandsome. The Sanskrit language is supremely elegant. The ç
gods in heaven are eternally young and vigorous. The Sanskrit language, ç
even now, is eternally fresh and delightfully vibrant.
Like all things in life, Sanskrit too has had its glorious periods ç
and spells of hibernation.
However, when India got political independence and its own government ç
there was a new upsurge of the national spirit enlivening every aspect ç
of Indian life. The Sanskrit language which had held the Hindu nation ç
together by its inspiring literature†whether sacred or secular† and ç
the resultant culture, could no longer remain insulated from this ç
new-found spirit.
@SPACE1 = 
Due to the patriotic zeal of some wiseand sagacious leaders, both ç
in the government and outside it, <%12>`<%0>The Sanskrit Commission'  was  constituted  by  the ç
Government of India on the 1st October 1956 with Dr. Suniti Kumar ç
Chatterji aneminent scholar and linguist, as thechairman, and seven ç
distinguished professors and savants as members.
@SPACE = 
The terms of reference were:
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
1. to undertake a survey of the existing facilities for Sanskrit Education ç
in Universities and non-University institutions and to make proposals ç
for promoting the study of Sanskrit, including research; and
@SPACE1 = 
2. to examine the traditional system of Sanskrit Education in order ç
to find out what features from it could be usefully incorporated into ç
the modern system.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
The  commission  established  its Secretariat at Poona (now Pune) ç
on the 1st November 1956.
@SPACE1 = 
It issued a detailed questionnaire† both in English and in Sanskrit†comprising ç
33 major questions, each containing several subquestions (85 in all) ç
covering all conceivable aspects of Sanskrit education and culture.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Apart from questions of a general nature, other aspects included in ç
the questionnaire were:
a.
@NK = Sanskrit Education†The Modern as well as the Traditional Systems;
b.
@NK = Sanskrit Research;
c.
@NK = Organisation and Administration of Sanskrit Studies and Education.
Apart from distinguished scholars and professors of Sanskrit, the ç
questionnaire was answered by a large number of persons from various ç
walks of life who were deeply interested in the spread of the language. ç
Nearly 1200 replies were received†about 470 being in Sanskrit† which ç
were analysed, the analyses themselves running into 2653 typed pages.
The Commission took the trouble ofcollecting all the reports of various ç
committees†eleven, to be more specific† appointed in the earlier years ç
by several State governments on the same subject of Sanskrit Education ç
and studied them.
Members of the Commission toured the country extensively, visited ç
most of the institutions connected with Sanskrit language and culture, ç
and interviewed hundreds of interested persons to elicit their opinions.
The final Report running into 300 pages (size: ??? ) was submitted ç
to the Government on 30th November 1957.
It  consists  of  12  chapters  and 9detailed appendices.
