@SB = A Brief Summary of the Report
@S10N = Chapter 1†Introduction
Apart from giving the details regarding the appointment of this Commission, ç
reference is made to the work of two Educational Commissions and the ç
Official Language Commission, all of which have touched upon the topic ç
of Sanskrit education. Various Sanskrit Reorganisation Commissions ç
appointed earlier by several State governments and Public Bodies have ç
also been referred to.
@S10N = Chapter 2†Historical Retrospect
This chapter gives a historical survey of Sanskrit studies in India, ç
especially after the taking over of the country by the British. Whereas ç
the old P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> system, the traditional system, ç
continued to survive, a new system, that of Colleges and  Universities  offering  courses  in ç
Sanskrit, also developed side by side. The growth of institutions ç
and activities on both these fronts over the last 150 years has been ç
described here.
@S10N = Chapter 3†The Present Situation
Activities of the P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s, Secondary Schools, Colleges, ç
Universities and Research  Institutions  as  also  various public ç
movements devoted to the promotion of Sanskrit in some form or the ç
other, have been reviewed here.
@S10N = Chapter 4†<|>Sanskrit and the<R>ç
Aspirations of Independent India
Realising the hopes and aspirations of the people of independent and ç
resurgent India,  this  chapter  discusses  various topics, opening ç
the case for Sanskrit. Some of them are: The importance of Sanskrit ç
in Indian History and Culture; Sanskrit studies and Humanities; intrinsic ç
worth and significance of Sanskrit literature for the full development ç
of human personality; Sanskrit as a binding force both at the national ç
and international levels; Sanskrit still a living force and a perennial ç
source for the sustenance of the various regional languages; must ç
be a part of general scheme of Indian education; should be accorded ç
special treatment.
@S10N = Chapter 5†Sanskrit Education
Sanskrit must be made one of the compulsory subjects in general education ç
as a part of the curriculum in the Secondary Schools. The specialised ç
studyin the P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s, in the modern Colleges and ç
Universities should be better organised. As a part of this subject, ç
the merits and drawbacks of the two systems are discussed as also ç
how the two can be integrated.
It has been pointed out here how Sanskrit has to be treated as a complement ç
to the higher study of modern Indian languages as also Indian Philosophy ç
and Indology.
@S10N = Chapter 6†Teaching of Sanskrit
Methods of teaching Sanskrit, both ancient and modern, have been described ç
here. The need to evolve suitable methods to teach it at different ç
levels as also thenecessary reforms in the system of examination ç
have been suggested.
@S10N = Chapter 7†Sanskrit Research
This chapter deals with Sanskrit Research in all its aspects. The ç
topics discussed are as follows: significance of research  for  the  growth  of  Sanskrit ç
studies;  research  in  the  Universities; research  scholarships  and  fellowships; ç
adjudication of research theses; neglected subjects; research projects ç
and research publications;  seminars;  Journals  and Bibliographies; ç
Research Institutions; All India Oriental Conference; a scheme for ç
a Central Institute of Indology.
@S10N = Chapter 8†Manuscripts
The question of Sanskrit Manuscripts has  been  tackled  here†their  search, ç
collection, preservation, cataloguing, study and publication.
It is advised to set up a Central Manuscripts library.
@S10N = Chapter 9†Sanskrit University
The question of setting up a Sanskrit University under the Central ç
Government has been suggested as also a Central Board of Sanskrit ç
Studies. States also can be encouraged to start similar Universities.
@S10N = Chapter 10†<R>ç
Other Questions concerning Sanskrit
The  following  topics  have  been discussed in this section: Sanskrit ç
and Religious Education; the use of regional scripts for Sanskrit; ç
Technical Termino-logy; Sanskrit as an Official Language of the Indian ç
Union; State honours and patronage for Sanskrit Scholars; encou-ragement ç
of Sanskrit through Ma<219>has and temples; Vedap<193><219>ha, Pur<193><207>ap<193><219>ha ç
and Paurohitya; technical disciplines like °yurveda, Jyauti<218>a ç
and <185>ilpa; Sanskrit journals; popularisation of Sanskrit by various ç
means; cheap editions of Sanskrit classics with translations in regional ç
languages and English.
@S10N = Chapter 11<%10>†<MI%0>Administration and	Organisation<R>ç
of Sanskrit Education and Research
The chief point that has been stressed is that the resources available ç
through various Trusts and Endowments should be pooled and utilised ç
for the promotion of Sanskrit.
@S10N = Chapter 12†Conspectus<|>and<|>Recommendations
This section gives a brief summary of  all  the  chapters  followed  by  the ç
Recommendations of the Commission.
@SB = Recommendations
@NID = <+><+><+><+>The Recommendations are categorised under the following ç
headings:
1. Sanskrit Education;
2. Sanskrit Research;
3. Manuscripts;
4. Sanskrit Universities;
5. General;
6. Administration and Organisation.
@S10N = 1.	Sanskrit Education
Sanskrit should be made a compulsory subject in the Secondary School ç
Curriculum.
The three Language Formula should be amended as follows:
a.
