The traditional P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> system should be continued ç
and preserved. It should be reorganised so as to include some modern ç
subjects like the mother-tongue, English, General Science, Mathematics ç
and Social Studies including Ancient Indian History and Culture.
The Pandit-Teachers should undergo a course of Teachers' Training.
The remodelled Sanskrit High Schools or remodelled P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s ç
should lead to Sanskrit Colleges.
The Pandit-Teachers should be treated as equal to Graduate-Teachers ç
in all respects.
In the College course leading up to the Graduate and Post-graduate ç
Degrees there should be a provision for the study of Sanskrit under ç
general as well as special subjects.
The  P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>  system  and  the University systems ç
should be retained as separate units, but gradually reformed tobring ç
about greater measure of co- operation between them.
The P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> Pandits should be employed to teach ç
in the modern Colleges and the professors of the latter, in the P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s, ç
for the betterment of both the systems.
In the Degree and Post-graduate courses in Indian languages and Humanities, ç
Sanskrit also should be one subject.
There should be an investigation into the methods of teaching Sanskrit ç
to different categories of students, Indian and foreign.
The P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> System has to be reformed by having ç
Sanskrit as the medium of instruction, at least at the higher level, ç
by introducing some subjects connected with Western thought and also ç
by adding suitable extra-curricular activities. The examination system ç
too needs drastic change. Oral examination of the old <185><193>str<193>rtha ç
type (discussion and disputation on holy texts) should be a part of ç
this new system of testing.
@S10N = 2.	Sanskrit Research
P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> Pandits too should be giventhe same facilities ç
for Research in the Universities and Colleges.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
High-grade Sanskrit Colleges with reputed Pandits on their staffs ç
and well-equipped libraries should be recognised by the Universities ç
for Research.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Critically editing and publishing rare manuscripts, starting of Research ç
Journals in Sanskrit, opening of Research Departments for different ç
<185><193>stras should be encouraged.
@SPACE1 = 
New Research Degrees like M.Litt., and D.Litt., should be introduced, ç
both having viva voce tests. Attention should be paid to the many ç
neglected fields demanding investigation by Research scholars. For ç
instance: Vedic Rituals; Kalpas<220>tras; <185>ilpa (Sculpturing); ç
Jyauti<218>a (Astronomy);   Iconography;   Sa<209>g<200>ta (Music); ç
N<193><219>ya (Dancing).
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Greater facilities should be offered for the publication of the results ç
of Research.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Manuscript libraries should be helped to bring out inventories and ç
even publications of the rare works.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Non-official Sanskrit and Indological Institutes in the country should ç
be brought under a comprehensive scheme of co- ordination and assisted ç
with liberal grants. A Central Institute of Indology should be established, ç
its core-section being devoted to Sanskrit.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
The All-India Oriental Conference should be placed on a permanent ç
basis with adequate financial assistance. It should be encouraged ç
to invite scholars from other Asian Countries.
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
Suitable Prizes and Awards should be instituted for Sanskrit and Indological ç
work.
@S10N = 3.	Manuscripts
@SPACE1 = 
@SPACE1 = 
A Central Manuscripts Survey should be established with branches in ç
different regions of the country. Its work should consist of Search, ç
Survey, Collection, Safeguard, Cataloguing and Publication of the ç
Manuscripts of Sanskrit and allied works.
The flow of manuscripts to foreign countries must be prevented by ç
all means.
The Manuscript Libraries should givefacilities to bona fide scholars ç
and institutions to consult or borrow them.
@SPACE = 
@S10N = 4.	Sanskrit Universities
Sanskrit  Universities  should  be established in different areas ç
to tone up and upgrade the traditional system of Sanskrit Education. ç
They should be the apex of the reorganised P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> ç
system. They should co-ordinate the working of the P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s ç
and Sanskrit Colleges. They should also function as Centres of Higher ç
Learning and Research in Sanskrit.
All the Sanskrit Universities should be under the aegis of the Central ç
Sanskrit Board, which must be a Statutory Body.
They should adopt Sanskrit medium at all levels, academic as well ç
as non- academic. They should also produce books in Sanskrit embodying ç
modern knowledge.
The Central Government should givea lead by establishing a centrally ç
administered Sanskrit University, preferably in South India.
@SPACE = 
@S10N = 5.	General
Sanskrit should be declared as an Additional Official Language.
Sanskrit should be officially used on all ceremonial occasions.
The infinite resources of Sanskrit literature like the Subh<193><218>itas ç
should be utilised in Schools and Colleges for moral instruction.
Efforts should be made to teach a Uniform  Standard  Pronunciation  of ç
Sanskrit in all parts of the country, by employing qualified readers ç
and teachers in areas where it is defective.
A comprehensive English-Sanskrit Dictionary of Scientific and Technical ç
Terms should be compiled with the help of suitable experts.
Personnel recruited for the Indian Administrative and Foreign Services ç
should be given opportunities through special courses of lectures ç
to acquire adequate knowledge of Sanskrit thought and Indian Culture. ç
Same policy can be adopted with regard to Indian students going abroad ç
for higher studies.
Indian Embassies abroad must haveCultural Attach<F14>Ç<F255>s possessing ç
special competence in Sanskrit Language, Literature and Culture.
Special attention should be made to preserve the Oral Tradition of ç
the different Vedas and their recensions as current in different parts ç
of India; and especially the S<193>maveda. Tape-recordings can be ç
made through the All India Radio*.
Steps should be taken to train the required personnel for the exposition ç
of Itih<193>sa-Pur<193><207>a. P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s should introduce ç
this also among their regular courses.
Gifted exponents of the R<193>m<193>ya<207>a, the Mah<193>bh<193>rata, ç
the G<200>t<193> and the pur<193><207>as should be employed in Community ç
Projects and National Extension Service Schemes to spread our culture ç
among the masses.
Courses in Paurohitya and Karma-k<193><207><195>a must be introduced ç
in the P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193>s.
Students  of  modern  science  and technology should be made familiar ç
with the developments made in our ancient and medieval periods as ç
per the standard works produced then.
Sanskrit should be popularised by adopting suitable measures. Some ç
of themare: organisation of private classes; producing Popular Sanskrit ç
booklets and selections with translations; celebration ofdays in ç
commemoration of important Sanskrit writers and works; simplification ç
of the methods of teaching Sanskrit; Sanskrit Literary Conferences; ç
promotion of Sanskrit debates and original writings in Sanskrit; competitions ç
in short stories, plays etc., in Sanskrit; musical recitals ofSanskrit ç
classics; enacting Sanskrit Dramas.
Important Sanskrit texts which are no longer available, should be ç
brought out in new editions by the Sahitya Akademi and other bodies.
@S10N = 6.	Administration and Organisation
A number of Trusts and Endowments formed for the promotion of Sanskrit ç
and allied purposes, now lying dormant, should be unearthed and be ç
put to use to implement the various proposals given in this report.
A Central Sanskrit Board should be constituted and run on the lines ç
of the University Grants Commission. It should concern itself mainly ç
with P<193><219>ha·<193>l<193> education and privately organised Research ç
Institutes in the country, by helping them in all possible manners. ç
It should be vested with the authority to sanction the starting of ç
Sanskrit Universities, to recognise them as statutory bodies, to give ç
them suitable grants and generally to control their working. It should ç
also co-operate with the Central Institute of Indology and the Central ç
Manuscripts Survey.
