@NT = <185><193>rad<193> script
Like the Br<193>hm<200> and the Kharo<218><219>h<200> scripts, the ç
<185><193>rad<193> script also is an ancient script that existed in ç
the Indian subconti-nent. It evolved from the Br<193>hm<200> script, ç
probably around the eighth century <MS>A.<|>D.<D>, in the north western ç
part like Dardistan, Kashmir, Jammu, Ladakh and Himachal Pradesh.
Alberuni (<MS>A.<|>D.<D> 970-1039), the Muslim traveller and historian, ç
has referred to this script as `Siddham<193>t<216>k<193>'.
It was the most popular script for several centuries extensively pervading ç
the areas of north-western India. The entire repertoire  of  extant  manuscripts  of ç
Sanskrit  and  old  Kashmiri  texts  of historical significance are ç
in this script. So also the several epigraphic records discovered ç
so far in this region.
The first printed edition of the famous work R<193>jatara<209>gi<207><200> ç
of Kalha<207>a (12th century <MS>A.<|>D.<D>) edited by Mark Aurel Stein ç
(<MS>A.<|>D.<D> 1862-1943) was based on a <185><193>rad<193> manuscript. ç
He also catalogued a large number of Sanskrit works in <185><193>rad<193> ç
script from the Raghunath Temple Library (inJammu).
This script was in vogue till the 13th Century <MS>A.<|>D.<D> It was ç
gradually replaced by its own evolution, the Deva·e<218>a, which again ç
gave rise to the modern Gurumukhi script.
The script still survives in the older generation of Pandits of Kashmir.
